  "prompt": "How does the catalyst affect the rate of reaction?",
  "response": "A catalyst affects the rate of reaction in several key ways:\n\n1. Lowering activation energy\n- Catalysts provide an alternative reaction pathway\n- This reduces the energy required to start the reaction\n- More reactant molecules can overcome the lower energy barrier\n- Results in faster reaction rate\n\n2. Creating intermediate compounds\n- Catalyst forms temporary chemical bonds with reactants\n- These intermediate compounds are more reactive\n- Helps molecules interact more easily\n\n3. Increasing collision frequency\n- Brings reactant molecules closer together\n- Increases probability of successful collisions\n- Makes chemical interactions more likely\n\n4. Unchanged after reaction\n- Catalyst is not consumed during the reaction\n- Remains available to facilitate subsequent reactions\n- Can continue catalyzing multiple reaction cycles\n\n5. Specificity\n- Different catalysts work for different reactions\n- Some are highly specific to particular chemical processes\n- Enzyme catalysts in biological systems are especially precise\n\n6. Reaction rate enhancement\n- Can increase reaction rates by factors of millions\n- Significantly reduces time required for chemical transformations\n\n7. Types of catalysts\n- Heterogeneous (different phase from reactants)\n- Homogeneous (same phase as reactants)\n- Biological catalysts (enzymes)\n\nThese mechanisms demonstrate how catalysts dramatically improve reaction efficiency.",
